1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 (3. Nf3 d5) 3... Bb4 (3... d5 {[%csl Ye2,Yg1]} 4.
cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Nge2) 4. Nf3 c5 $1 {Karpov
eventually settled on this line as Black's most reliable reply to 4 Nf3.} 5. g3
{Kasparov's line from the 1980-es matches vs. Karpov} Nc6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4)
6. Bg2 Ne4 $1 {Black immediately attacks White's center with pieces, in the
spirit of the Nimzo-Indian. Especially the diagonal e1-a5 comes under attack
by Black's pieces.} 7. Bd2 (7. Qd3 Qa5 $5 8. Qxe4 (8. Bd2 Nxd2 9. Qxd2 cxd4 10.
Nxd4 {[%cal Ya5e1]}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 Nxd4) 7... Bxc3 (7...
Nxd2 $5 {is the solid alternative for Black.} 8. Qxd2 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Ne5 10. Nc2
Nxc4 (10... Be7 11. Ne3 $14) 11. Qd4 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 Qa5 $1 {forcing b2-b4} 13.
b4 Qc7 14. Qxg7 Qe5 15. Qxe5 Nxe5 {with a very slight advantage for White
according to Kasparov, but this is fully playable for Black. 7...Bxc3 is more
ambitious for Black.}) 8. Bxc3 (8. bxc3 {is the more ambitious alternative for
White.}) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. O-O d6 11. Qd3 cxd4 $1 {An instructive and
important moment in this (short) game. I did not want to allow White to follow
the same plan as in Khalifman-Chiburdanidze with Rf1, dxc5, and Qd6 when White
controls thw open c-file. So instead I used an idea which has been popularized
by Karpov and others in similar positions: allowing White to undouble his
c-pawns, but in return Black gets control of the dark squares.} 12. cxd4 e5 $1
13. Rfd1 {The game was drawn here on Agrest's proposal. It could have
continued like this:} Qe7 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Qd6 {[%csl Yc5] Same idea as
Khalifman. But if you compare this game to Khalifman-Chirburdanidze, the lack
of pawns on c3 and c5 favors Black. Why?} Qxd6 16. Rxd6 Be6 $1 $11 {and Black
is absolutely fine because he can immediately begin to attack White's isolated
c-pawn (whereas Black had no way to attack the doubled c-pawns in
Khalifman-Chiburdanideze). This is an important point highlighted by Lasker:
PAWN WEAKNESSES ARE ONLY REALLY WEAKNESSES IF THEY CAN BE ATTACKED!} 1/2-1/2

