1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3 c5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Ne4 7. Bd2 Bxc3 8.
bxc3 (8. Bxc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {[%csl Yd1,Yd2]}) 8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2 {[%csl Yd1,Yd2]
Now White has an extra tempo over my game with Agrest because the queen is
already on d2. This is important as we shall see. For this reason, if Agrest
had played 8 bxc3, I would not have taken on d2.} d6 10. O-O O-O 11. Rfd1 Qe7
12. Rab1 $1 {This is the dynamic features White gets in return for the doubled
pawn - a lead in development with active pieces and control of opehn and
half-open files.} Rb8 13. dxc5 $1 dxc5 14. Qd6 $1 {[%csl Yc3,Yc4] White uses
his lead in deveopment to take control of the now ope d-file.} Qxd6 15. Rxd6
Na5 16. Ne5 b6 17. Rbd1 f6 18. Nc6 $1 Nxc6 19. Bxc6 {[%csl Yc3,Yc4] Now the
knights got traded, which clearly favors White, because now Black has less
counterplay vs. the double c-pawns while his control of the d-files becomes 
even more important.} f5 (19... Ba6 20. Bb5 Bxb5 21. cxb5 $16) 20. f4 Ba6 21.
Bb5 Bxb5 22. cxb5 $16 Rbe8 23. Rd7 Rf7 24. Kf2 {[%cal Yf2f3,Ye2e4]} e5 $6 25.
Rd8 Rxd8 26. Rxd8+ Rf8 27. Rxf8+ Kxf8 28. fxe5 $18 {The pawn endgame is
winning for White.} Kf7 29. Kf3 g5 30. h4 Ke6 31. hxg5 Kxe5 32. g4 f4 33. a4 c4
34. e4 fxe3 35. Kxe3 Kd5 36. Kf4 Ke6 37. Ke4 Kf7 38. Kd5 Kg6 39. Kc6 Kxg5 40.
